Yes =E2=80=94 that *is* the PWM=E2=80=91related DTS node, but more precisel=
y:

=F0=9F=91=89 *It is the device=E2=80=91tree node for the Renesas GPT (Gener=
al PWM Timer)
block*,
which *provides* PWM channels to the Linux PWM subsystem.

Let me break it down so you can see exactly what each part means.
------------------------------
=F0=9F=A7=A0 What this DTS node represents

gpt1_4: gpt@13020400 {
    compatible =3D "renesas,gpt-r9a09g047";
    reg =3D <0 0x13020400 0 0xa4>;
    #pwm-cells =3D <2>;
    interrupts =3D <...>;
    clocks =3D <&cpg CPG_MOD 0x32>;
    power-domains =3D <&cpg>;
    resets =3D  <&cpg 0x5B>,<&cpg 0x5C>;
    status =3D "disabled";
};

This is *one GPT hardware block* inside the SoC.

Renesas GPT =3D *General PWM Timer*
=E2=86=92 It can generate PWM signals
=E2=86=92 It can also be used as a timer/counter

Linux exposes it through the *PWM subsystem*.
------------------------------
=F0=9F=94=A7 Key fields explained =E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F compatible =3D "renesa=
s,gpt-r9a09g047";

This tells Linux which driver to bind.
This is the GPT driver for RZ/G3S (R9A09G047).
------------------------------
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F reg =3D <...>

The MMIO register range for this GPT instance.
------------------------------
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F #pwm-cells =3D <2>;

This is the important part for PWM.

It means:

<pwm-channel period-ns flags>

So a PWM consumer node can reference this GPT like:

pwm =3D <&gpt1_4 0 20000000 0>;

------------------------------
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F interrupts =3D <...>

GPT has multiple channels (A, B, C, D, E, F, H, I).
Each channel has its own interrupt.
------------------------------
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F clocks, power-domains, resets

Standard Renesas SoC integration.
------------------------------
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F status =3D "disabled";

This node is disabled by default.
A board DTS must enable it:

&gpt1_4 {
    status =3D "okay";
};

------------------------------
=F0=9F=A7=A9 So is this the PWM DTS? =E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F Yes =E2=80=94 this =
is the *PWM controller* node

It registers a PWM provider (pwmchipN) in Linux.
=E2=9D=8C It is NOT a PWM consumer

It does not define the PWM output pin or how it is used.

A consumer node (like LED, backlight, buzzer, motor) would reference this
GPT using:

pwm =3D <&gpt1_4 0 20000000 0>;

------------------------------
=F0=9F=A7=A0 How this maps to sysfs

Once enabled, Linux will create:

/sys/class/pwm/pwmchipX/

Where pwmchipX corresponds to this GPT block.

Then you can:

echo 0 > pwmchipX/export
echo 20000000 > pwmchipX/pwm0/period
echo 1000000  > pwmchipX/pwm0/duty_cycle
echo 1 > pwmchipX/pwm0/enable

This produces a *continuous PWM waveform*.
------------------------------
If you want, I can also show you:

   - How to write a PWM consumer node in DTS
   - How to map GPT pins using pinctrl
   - How to verify which pwmchip corresponds to which GPT
   - How to generate a single pulse instead of continuous PWM

Just tell me where you want to go next.

